Alright, so you want to select all checkboxes on a page with JavaScript and then save their state when you click a "Save" button. Here's how you can do it:

1. First, make sure you have a way to reference all the checkboxes. You can use `document.querySelectorAll` to grab them by their type or class.
2. Then, add an event listener to your "Save" button that loops through all the checkboxes and saves their checked state.

Here’s a quick example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Checkbox Automation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="checkbox" id="check1"> Check 1<br>
    <input type="checkbox" id="check2"> Check 2<br>
    <input type="checkbox" id="check3"> Check 3<br>

    <button id="saveButton">Save</button>

    <script>
        // Get all checkboxes
        const checkboxes = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]');

        // Add event listener to the Save button
        document.getElementById('saveButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            checkboxes.forEach(checkbox => {
                // Save the checked state of each checkbox (for demonstration, we'll just log it)
                console.log(`${checkbox.id}: ${checkbox.checked}`);
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example:
- We select all checkboxes using `document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]')`.
- We attach an event listener to the "Save" button.
- When the button is clicked, it loops through all the checkboxes and logs their ID and checked state to the console.

If you want to actually save these states to local storage or send them to a server, you can modify the code to do that instead of logging them. For instance, you could store the checked states in local storage like this:

```javascript
document.getElementById('saveButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
    const checkboxStates = {};
    checkboxes.forEach(checkbox => {
        checkboxStates[checkbox.id] = checkbox.checked;
    });

    localStorage.setItem('checkboxStates', JSON.stringify(checkboxStates));
});
```

This way, the states are stored in `localStorage`, and you can retrieve them later if needed.

